@database WOOKIECHAT DOCUMENTATION
@node main "WOOKIECHAT DOCUMENTATION"

                          @{b}WOOKIECHAT DOCUMENTATION@{ub}@{fg text}


      WookieChat is a program for chatting on Internet Relay Chat networks.
      Written by James Carroll.

      @{" ABOUT IRC          " link "aboutirc"} Introduction to IRC
      @{" BASIC IRC COMMANDS " link "commands"} Basic everyday stuff
      @{" OP STATUS COMMANDS " link "statcommands"} Controlling a channel
      @{" MORE COMMANDS      " link "morecom"} More advanced commands
      @{" WOOKIECHAT DISPLAY " link "wcdisplay"} The user interface explained
      @{" DCC SEND           " link "dcc"} Advanced topic for file sending


      Requirements:
      - AmigaOS4.0
      - MUI Custom Classes: BetterString.mcc, NList.mcc, NListtree.mcc
        (all downloadable from http://OS4depot.net)

@endnode

@node aboutirc "ABOUT IRC"

                           @{b}ABOUT IRC@{fg text}@{ub}


      IRC stands for Internet Relay Chat. IRC is a Network where people 
      can chat (type) with each other from all over the world. Chats can 
      be with groups of people in a channel, and with individuals as a 
      private chat. 

      There are many IRC Networks. Some popular ones are Undernet, DALnet, 
      EFNet. There may be 100s of IRC Networks. 

      Each IRC Network may have thousands of channels (also known as chat 
      rooms) 

      A channel might have anything between 1 and 1000 people chatting 
      together. 

      Examples of channel names are #usa, #amiga, #nz, #london, #islam, 
      #chatzone, #philosophy, covering any subject that people talk about. 
      If a channel doesn't exist then one can easily create their own 
      channel, and invite people to join. 

      Each person can choose their own alias (or "nick") to be identified 
      by. A person can be in multiple channels at any one time. 

      Channels usually have rules. Every channel has at least one person 
      with Op (Operator) status. Such people have the power to force other 
      users out of the channel, usually for a rule broken, for swearing 
      etc. Ops can grant other people Op status. 

      Each IRC Network has multiple servers. If a person cannot connect to 
      a particular server, or if messages are being received with a great 
      delay, they may be able to get a better connection on another 
      server. A good connection will be able to have messages received 
      within 5 seconds. People usually get frustrated if a message is 
      taking 10 seconds or minutes to be received. 

@endnode

@node commands "BASIC IRC COMMANDS"

                      @{b}BASIC IRC COMMANDS@{fg text}@{ub}



      IRC commands are usually typed in text entry bar, or accessed with 
      the mouse. 

      IRC commands that are typed are usually preceeded with a "/" slash 
      character. 

      @{b}[CONNECT TO AN IRC NETWORK]@{ub}
      /server eu.undernet.org  {press enter}
       Attempts to connect to the eu.undernet.org server.
       > WITH MOUSE
       > Select Main menu, then "Select server"

      @{b}[JOIN A CHANNEL]@{ub}
       When connected to a server, you can then join a channel.
      /join #london  {press enter}
       Joins the #london channel.

      @{b}[SEND A MESSAGE TO A CHANNEL]@{ub}
       While in a channel, you can send & receive messages with all people 
      in the channel.  Just type normally. 
       Sending a message to a channel doesn't require the preceeding "/" 
      slash character. 

      hi everyone  {press enter}

      @{b}[NICKLIST]@{ub}
       On the right side of the channel window is the list of people in the channel.

      @{b}[CONTEXT MENU]@{ub}
       The context menu has a list of commonly used functions:

       > WITH MOUSE
       > Click on a person in Nicklist.
       > Rightclick to access the context menu.
         Note, use Shift+Click to select multiple people.

      @{b}[LIST NAMES OF PEOPLE IN A CHANNEL]@{ub}
      /names #london  {press enter}
       Lists the people in the #london channel.

      @{b}[SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE TO ONE PERSON]@{ub}
      /msg angel777 hi sara
       Sends a private message "hi sara" to angel777 only.

      @{b}[THE "ME" COMMAND]@{ub}
      /me thinks david is correct  {press enter}
       Sends a message in the format "henrybob thinks david is correct"

      @{b}[LEAVE A CHANNEL]@{ub}
      /part  {press enter}
       Leave the channel you are in, or, closes the query window you are in:

       > WITH MOUSE
       > Select Main menu, then "Close current tab"
      OR
       > Press the "X" button in the top left hand corner

      @{b}[PING ANOTHER USER]@{ub}
      /ping angel777  {press enter}
       Checks how much time it takes for angel777 to receive your message.

      @{b}[OPEN A PRIVATE CHAT WINDOW]@{ub}
      /query angel777  {press enter}
       Opens a window for private chat with angel777.
      Also, typing "/query angel777 hello there" will message the person 
      at the same time 

      @{b}[SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE IN A PRIVATE CHAT WINDOW]@{ub}
       While a query window is open, you can send & receive messages with 
      angel777.  Just type normally. 

       Sending a message to a query window doesn't require the preceeding 
      "/" slash character. 

      hi sarah  {press enter}

      @{b}[CHANGE YOUR NAME]@{ub}
      /nick henrybob  {press enter}
       Changes your alias to henrybob.

      @{b}[DISPLAY A PERSON'S INFO]@{ub}
      /whois angel777  {press enter}
       Provides some basic information about angel777's connection.
       Also checks to see whether angel777 is connected.

      @{b}[LEAVE AN AWAY MESSAGE]@{ub}
      /away back in a bit  {press enter}
       Leaves a short message for people, letting them know you are away.
       People will get this message when they try to contact you.
      /away  {press enter}
       When the away command is used without a message, it will remove the 
      away status. 

      @{b}[DISCONNECT FROM IRC NETWORK]@{ub}
      /quit  {press enter}
       Disconnect from the irc server you are connected to.

@endnode

@node statcommands "OP STATUS COMMANDS"

                    @{b}OP STATUS COMMANDS@{fg text}@{ub}



      Only people who have Op status in a channel may use these commands.

      @{b}[SET CHANNEL TOPIC]@{ub}
      /topic Welcome to #london  {press enter}
       Sets the channel's topic line to "Welcome to #london"

      @{b}[GRANT OP STATUS]@{ub}
      /op angel777  {press enter}
       Grants Op status to angel777 (for the channel you are in)

      @{b}[REMOVE OP STATUS]@{ub}
      /deop angel777  {press enter}
       Removes Op status from angel777 (for the channel you are in)

      @{b}[BAN USER FROM CHANNEL]@{ub}
      /ban angel777  {press enter}
       Removes angel777's ability to send messages to the channel.
       Also removes angel777's ability to rejoin the channel.
       Note, /ban does not force someone out of a channel,
             (see "/kick" to force someone out of a channel)

      @{b}[KICK USER FROM CHANNEL]@{ub}
      /kick angel777  {press enter}
       Forces angel777 out of the channel.

      @{b}[UNBAN A USER]@{ub}
      /unban angel777  {press enter}
       Re-enables angel777's ability to send messages to the channel.
       Also re-enables angel777's ability to join the channel.

      @{b}[INVITE A USER INTO A CHANNEL]@{ub}
      /invite angel777 #london
       Invites angel777 to join channel #london

@endnode

@node morecom "MORE COMMANDS"

                        @{b}MORE COMMANDS@{fg text}@{ub}



      @{b}[CTCP COMMAND]@{ub}
       Ctcp has a range of features. Here are two.
      /ctcp angel777 version  {press enter}
       Shows what IRC program and program version angel777 is using.
      /ctcp angel777 time  {press enter}
       Displays angel777 time.

      @{b}[VERSION]@{ub}
      /version angel777  {press enter}
       Shows what IRC program and program version angel777 is using.
       (just like /ctcp angel777 version)

      @{b}[SEND A FILE TO ANOTHER PERSON]@{ub}
       Files can be sent & received between individuals on IRC.
      /dcc send angel777 dh0:photos/100_5854.jpg  {press enter}
       Sends dh0:photos/100_5854.jpg file to user angel777
         > WITH MOUSE
         > Click on a person
         > Rightclick to get Context menu
         > Direct Connection
         > Send file

      @{b}[CONNECT TO ANOTHER NETWORK]@{ub}
       One may join multiple networks:
         > WITH MOUSE
         > Select Main menu, then "Select Server"
         > Click on a server of your choice
         > Click on "Connect in New TAB"

      @{b}[GLOBAL QUERY]@{ub}
       Opens a window for all private messages to be received into.
       Handy if you are receiving a lot of private messages.
       Note, you cannot send messages to people from the global query window.
             use /query angel777 to open a query window for private chat 
             with one individual: 
         > WITH MOUSE
         > Select Main menu, then "Open global query tab"

      @{b}[HIGHLIGHT]@{ub}
       Choose important text you want highlighted (yellow by default)
         > WITH MOUSE
         > Select Settings menu, then "main settings"
         > Go to "General" tab
         > Go to "Words to Highlight"
         > Type words you want highlighted

      @{b}[PERFORM ON CONNECT]@{ub} 
       A list of commands can be made, to happen each time connecting to a 
       particular network. One may like to join the #london channel every 
       time they join the Undernet IRC Network: 
         > WITH MOUSE
         > Select Main menu, then "Select Server"
         > Click on Undernet.
         > Click on "Perform on connect"
           (A text editor will appear)
         > Type /join #london  {press enter}
         > Save and close.

       Now everytime you connect to Undernet, channel #london will be 
      joined automatically. 

      @{b}[SELECT FAVOURITE TEXT EDITOR]@{ub} 
      Choose the text editing program you prefer, to edit "perform on 
      connect" scripts with. 
         > WITH MOUSE
         > Select Settings menu, then "Main Settings"
         > Go to "General" tab
         > Go to "Text Editor" section

      @{b}[CHANNEL CYCLING]@{ub}
      Leave and rejoin a channel straight away.
      /cycle {hit enter}

      @{b}[SENDING RAW TEXT]@{ub} 
      /raw and /quote will both send raw text to the server. This can be 
      useful when using a command not currently supported directly by 
      WookieChat. 

      If you type a command with a "/" prefix that isnt supported by 
      WookieChat yet, it will remove the "/" from the start of the line 
      and send the rest of the text raw to the server automatically. 

@endnode

@node wcdisplay "WOOKIECHAT DISPLAY"

                       @{b}WOOKIECHAT DISPLAY@{fg text}@{ub}


      @{b}[DISPLAY]@{ub}
      On Joining a channel, the WookieChat Displays the following:

      [Close Button]
      [Topic String Gadget]

      Buttons for Ops only:

      @{b}[T]@{ub} Topic protection - prevents non ops from changing the channel's 
          topic. 
      @{b}[N]@{ub} No messaging - prevents people from outside the channel sending 
          in messages. 
      @{b}[S]@{ub} Secret mode  - "If this is set, the channel is invisible until 
          you have joined" 
      @{b}[I]@{ub} Invite only  - only people who have been invited with /invite 
          command may join. 
      @{b}[P]@{ub} Private mode - "If set, channel topic is not shown on global 
          channel lists" 
      @{b}[M]@{ub} Moderated mode - prevents non ops from chatting in the channel.
      @{b}[K]@{ub} Keyword mode   - causes people to require a password to join.
      @{b}[L]@{ub} Limit mode     - sets a limit of the maximum number of people 
          who may join. 

      @{b}[Channel]@{ub} - main chat display, located on left side of screen, black 
          background. 

      @{b}[Nicklist]@{ub} - located on right side of screen. blue background.
      @{b}[Text Entry Bar]@{ub} - located bottom of screen. Type your commands and 
          messages here. 
      @{b}[Tabs Bar]@{ub} - located below the Text Entry gadget, at the very bottom 
          of WookieChat. Shows which Channels and other query windows are 
          open. 

      @{b}[TAB ALERT]@{ub}
      Tabs will show coloured square bullet points when a window has new 
      text:

      []Blue  - someone has joined, parted, changed nick, or other status 
         or change. 
      []Red   - someone has sent a message.
      []Green - someone has sent a message which contains your nick or 
         which has text you wanted highlighted.   (See "HIGHLIGHT" to
         choose important text you want highlighted) 

@endnode

@node dcc "DCC SEND"

                           @{b}DCC SEND@{fg text}@{ub}


      When you try to send a file to another user on IRC, WookieChat will 
      (in an initiating message) tell the other persons IRC client the 
      address of your computer, and the port on your computer to connect 
      to. If you are behind a firewall, you need to "open up" some ports, 
      and configure WookieChat to use that port range. By default, 
      WookieChat uses ports 1025 to 1035. If you are not happy with this, 
      it is easily changed from the DCC Settings tab in the Main Settings 
      window. 

      Please refer to your firewall or routers manual on opening up ports 
      as they may vary. You may need to use a "static IP address". On my 
      machine for example, I give my Amiga an IP address of 
      "192.168.1.10". Then in the routers firewall configuration, I map a 
      port range from 1025 to 1035 for that address (192.168.1.10). My 
      Amiga is now ready to accept incoming connections. 

      Unfortunately, I have been able to get file transfers working on 
      every network. DCC SEND has been a little fiddly to get working 100% 
      on other platforms and IRC clients as well. I have been able to get 
      it running on the AfterX network at least. 

      If you want to send files across a local network, you can tick the 
      "Use local address for DCC connections" option in the DCC Settings 
      tab. Make sure to change it back before trying to send outside the 
      LAN though! 

@endnode

